    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 316648,
      "reputation" : 1745,
      "user_id" : 632931,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9d0a48c2ab9fe6f5338a15b357fec721?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "MisterEd",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/632931/mistered"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1630106559,
    "last_edit_date" : 1630106559,
    "creation_date" : 1381938777,
    "answer_id" : 19408042,
    "question_id" : 2896727,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The JDK 1.6 I'm currently using on <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OS_X_Mountain_Lion\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">OS X v10.8</a> (Mountain Lion) did not come with a <code>src.zip</code> either, and as far as I can tell there is no supported Mac OS X JDK for 1.6 available anymore.</p>\n<p>So I downloaded the OpenJDK source (using the links from the accepted answer (+1)) then ran:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>cd ~/Downloads\nmkdir jdk6src\ncd jdk6src\ntar xf ../openjdk-6-src-b27-26_oct_2012.tar.gz\ncd jdk/src/share/classes\njar cf /System/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/1.6.0.jdk/Contents/Home/src.jar *\n</code></pre>\n<p>(Your file names and paths may vary...)</p>\n<p>Associate that <code>src.jar</code> with the appropriate Java platform in your IDE and you should be good to go.</p>\n<p>There are some discrepancies between the OpenJDK source and the JDK I'm currently running (line numbers don't match up in the debugger, for one), but if all you want is a zip/jar to point your IDE to for the relatively few cases you need to peek at some code to understand how something works, then this should do the trick.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 111356,
      "reputation" : 1379,
      "user_id" : 294214,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 58,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/56fc4c400bd45ba8121b7897b389361d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "amertkara",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/294214/amertkara"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 39,
    "last_activity_date" : 1630106908,
    "last_edit_date" : 1630106908,
    "creation_date" : 1429888075,
    "answer_id" : 29851051,
    "question_id" : 2896727,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Chances that you already got the source code with the JDK, is a matter of finding where it is. In that case, the JDK folder doesn't contain the source code:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>sudo apt-get install openjdk-7-source\n</code></pre>\n<p>OS X folks, search in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homebrew_(package_manager)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Homebrew</a> formulas.</p>\n<p>In Ubuntu, the command above would put your source file under:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-none prettyprint-override\"><code>/usr/lib/jvm/openjdk-7/\n</code></pre>\n<p>The good news is that Eclipse will take you there already (how to bind Eclipse to the Java source code):</p>\n<p>Follow the orange buttons</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/AiAYS.png\" alt=\"Enter image description here\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/Djbda.png\" alt=\"Enter image description here\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/uHmBJ.png\" alt=\"Enter image description here\" /></p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 546657,
