    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "user4229245"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 18,
    "last_activity_date" : 1630106755,
    "last_edit_date" : 1630106755,
    "creation_date" : 1430524566,
    "answer_id" : 29996760,
    "question_id" : 2896727,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Sadly, as of this writing, <em>despite</em> their own documentation readme, there is <em>no</em> src.zip in the JDK 7 or 8 install directories <em><strong>when you download the Windows version</strong></em>.</p>\n<p>Note: perhaps this happens because many of us don't actually run the install .exe, but instead extract it.  Many of us don't run the Java install (the full blown Windows install) for security reasons...we just want the JDK put someplace out of the way where potential viruses cannot find it.</p>\n<p>But their policy regarding the Windows .exe (whatever it truly is) is indeed nuts, <em><strong>however</strong></em>, the src.zip <em><strong>DOES</strong></em> exist in the Linux install (a .tar.gz).  There are multiple ways of extracting a .tar and a .gz, and I prefer the free &quot;7Zip&quot; utility.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>download the Linux 64 bit .tar.gz</li>\n<li>use <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7-Zip\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">7-Zip</a> to uncompress the .tar.gz to a .tar</li>\n<li>use 7-Zip to extract the .tar to the installation directory</li>\n<li>File <em>src.zip</em> will be waiting for you in that installation directory.</li>\n<li>pull it out and place it where you like.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Oracle, this is really beyond stupid.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4859241,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 3919395,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0acb5b3564d4099e01bcb5129e7bab22?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "petery",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3919395/petery"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1630106798,
    "last_edit_date" : 1630106798,
    "creation_date" : 1430545731,
    "answer_id" : 29998950,
    "question_id" : 2896727,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Well, I opened terminal in my Mac and typed:</p>\n<pre><code>echo $JAVA_HOME\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then I got the directory, went there and found src.zip.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3031224,
      "reputation" : 3890,
      "user_id" : 2570189,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 17,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/FlQvh.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "dvsakgec",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2570189/dvsakgec"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1630107038,
    "last_edit_date" : 1630107038,
    "creation_date" : 1479404897,
    "answer_id" : 40661727,
    "question_id" : 2896727,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In JDK 8, the source can be found in <em>&lt;JDK installation directory&gt;/src.zip</em>. Now in some intermediate releases this ZIP file was missing, but again it is available.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/pUfwY.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/pUfwY.png\" alt=\"Enter image description here\" /></a></p>\n<p>Make sure that you select the source as well from the installation wizard.</p>\n"
  } ],
